    <node id="1. The Welsh Government, in collaboration with Universities Wales and representatives of the Welsh higher education sector, is aiming to provide stability for the next academic year and support the sector through these challenging times by releasing as much money as possible to help universities get through this initial period of difficulty. This aligns with one of the key proposals from Universities UK, which emphasizes the need for financial support to ensure university sustainability.&#10;2. The Welsh Government is also participating in discussions with relevant bodies in Wales, Northern Ireland, Scotland, and the Westminster Government, as well as UCAS, to address issues related to student entry into universities due to the pandemic. This includes discussions on the moratorium on unconditional offers for university admission, which is another concern raised by Universities UK.&#10;3. Additionally, the Welsh Government is working with NUS Wales and counterparts across the UK to provide financial support for students impacted by changes in their study arrangements due to the pandemic. This addresses another issue raised by Universities UK, which highlights the need for student financial support during this time. The Welsh Government's efforts demonstrate a commitment to addressing the challenges faced by both universities and students in light of the pandemic, with measures that are consistent with the proposals put forward by Universities UK." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is aware of the digital divide issue and is working with local authorities to ensure that all children have access to necessary hardware and connectivity for remote learning.&#10;2. They have purchased software to convert old pieces of equipment into out-of-the-box Chromebooks, utilizing existing stock in schools and local authorities.&#10;3. A national level purchase and distribution of Mi-Fi connectivity will be made to address connectivity issues, providing Wi-Fi access for students who lack it.&#10;4. These measures aim to ensure equal opportunity and access to learning during this time, reducing inequality due to varying digital resources." />
    <node id=" I just ask this one question?&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: No, that's fine. Yes, go on.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Your comment, Minister, on working with local authorities to make sure that individuals have hardware: can you just give us a bit of detail on what working with local authorities actually means? In the process of that, is there any data gathering going on for those pupils who are being educated at home and the levels at which they're engaging? You know, are they sticking with it, or how many are dropping out? Because I think the two of those perhaps go together.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, absolutely. So, I'm hoping to make an announcement tomorrow, if not later on this week, about some specific details around support for hardware and connectivity. We're working closely with local authorities to understand just that: to understand from the schools the number of schools that—and a number of them have already done this—have been lending Chromebooks, iPads and laptops to children, and also identifying children who are not perhaps engaging in the activities that have been made available. And we'll be doing two things to support local authorities. The first" />
    <node id=" and also identifying children who are not perhaps engaging in the activities that have been made available. And we'll be doing two things to support local authorities. The first is to use the stock of equipment that they already have to be able to provide hardware to students. So, we have purchased on a national basis software that, when applied to an old piece of kit, essentially turns it into an out-of-the-box Chromebook. Because, as you can imagine, just like other things during a pandemic, there has been a rush to buy new stuff on the market and then there is a scramble and nobody can get what they need. So, we're utilisng kit that is already available in schools and local authorities, and we will look to backfill that to schools at a later point out of our EdTech investment programme. The other issue is, once a child has a Chromebook or a laptop or a device, issues around connectivity. So, we're also looking to purchase on a national level and distribute Mi-Fi connectivity, so students will be able to have access to Wi-Fi where they don't have that already. That's why we need to work closely with local authorities and schools to identify the level of that need and to make sure the stuff" />
    <node id="1. Dawn Bowden AM is temporarily chairing the committee while Lynne Neagle AM tries to rejoin the meeting.&#10;2. The agenda for this afternoon's evidence session includes:&#10;   - A welcome and opening statement from Kirsty Williams AM, Minister for Education.&#10;   - An appreciation statement from the Minister regarding those who have helped during the pandemic, particularly those who have kept school hubs open, looked after vulnerable children, and the children of key workers.&#10;   - A discussion with Kirsty Williams AM, Steve Davies (director of the education directorate), and Huw Morris (group director, skills, higher education and lifelong learning) on the impact of the coronavirus epidemic on education in Wales." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is working closely with local authorities to understand the number of schools that have been lending technological devices such as Chromebooks, iPads, and laptops to children. This collaboration aims to identify children who are not engaging in remote learning activities and assess the level of need for hardware and connectivity support.&#10;2. To ensure resources reach the right children effectively, the Government is trying to do this on a national basis by deploying required technological resources to local authorities. This approach aims to assist local authorities in obtaining necessary resources in the crowded market.&#10;3. The Government is repurposing some of the previously identified resources from their EdTech investment to fill the gaps in hardware and connectivity support, particularly for children who do not have access to technology for remote learning." />
    <node id=" don't have that already. That's why we need to work closely with local authorities and schools to identify the level of that need and to make sure the stuff gets to the right children. One of the ways in which we are able to do that is to look at engagement in education. So, if a child hasn't been engaging, is that because they just don't want to and they're voting with their feet—but clearly teachers need to have a conversation about that—or is that because the child simply does not have the ability to do that, and therefore we need to get that stuff out to those children? So, rather than just simply leaving it to local authorities to scramble around in a very crowded market to get the stuff that they will need, we're trying to do that on a national basis and deploy that to local authorities. So, our officials have been having conversations with each of our local authorities to ascertain what's already happened, and there is very good practice out there—schools have been proactive—but where there are gaps, what can we do as a national Government to be able to assist them to do that? We are repurposing some of the resources that we had previously identified for our EdTech investment, using those resources to fill this" />
    <node id="Based on the meeting transcripts, the Welsh Government is not currently considering a relaxation of truancy rules or providing specific guidance for schools regarding relaxing attendance requirements. Instead, the focus is on ensuring appropriate referral mechanisms are in place for teachers or anyone who has concerns about a child, and that schools should continue to identify vulnerable children and refer them to children's services if needed. Schools are expected to remain in contact with children during this time. While there has been no explicit mention of relaxing lockdown rules for children, the Welsh Government seems open to considering measures to support these children in future phases of education in the new normal. The main emphasis is on ensuring stability for the next academic year and supporting the education sector through these challenging times by releasing as much money as possible to help institutions get through this initial period of difficulty." />
    <node id="The Welsh Government is actively addressing the risk of inequality in children's education rights during the pandemic by recognizing the importance of equal opportunity and access to learning. They are aware of the potential increase in the attainment gap between disadvantaged pupils and their more affluent peers due to unequal access to technology. Officials are working with local authorities to ensure all children have access to necessary hardware and connectivity, which is crucial for continued learning and the deployment of tools like Adobe Spark nationally. This proactive approach aims to prevent the attainment gap from widening and ensure that every child in Wales has equal opportunities in education during these challenging times." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is working on several fronts to address the challenges faced by students due to the pandemic. This includes providing financial support for students impacted by changes in their study arrangements and advising them to discuss waiving or partially waiving accommodation fees with providers.&#10;2. Discussions are taking place between relevant bodies in Wales, Northern Ireland, Scotland, and the Westminster Government, as well as UCAS, to address issues related to student entry into universities due to the pandemic.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is working with NUS Wales and counterparts across the UK to provide financial support for students.&#10;4. Teachers in Wales will submit estimated grades for A-level and GCSE qualifications based on a range of data and professional judgment, which will then be moderated by Qualifications Wales to ensure fairness and consistency.&#10;5. Suzy Davies AM acknowledges the efforts of some accommodation providers who have waived or partially waived fees for students and mentions the Universities UK document detailing difficulties faced by universities during the pandemic. She also confirms that the Welsh Government is continuing dialogue with NUS Wales and counterparts across the country to explore further support for students.&#10;&#10;In response to the question, while there is no specific mention of measures addressing the cancellation of programs such as the Yale global summer school, the Welsh Government is making efforts to ensure students continue to have access to resources and advice for learning and future decision-making through various financial support initiatives, discussions on student entry into universities, and maintaining a robust qualifications system for awarding A-level and GCSE qualifications." />
    <node id="1. Professional Expectations for Reporting and Referring Cases: There is a professional expectation for all those working with children and young people, including in specialist hubs, to continue reporting and referring cases if they have concerns about a child's welfare and safety. This responsibility applies even during the current circumstances when face-to-face contact may be limited.&#10;2. Challenges in Specialist Hubs: Specialist hubs for children with additional learning needs can present challenges related to staffing. These hubs often operate on a rota basis, which means that children might interact with staff they are unfamiliar with, potentially impacting their health and well-being.&#10;3. Importance of Maintaining Communication: To support children with additional learning needs during this time, it is essential for schools to maintain regular contact with them. This can help keep children engaged and supported, especially for young children who might not respond well to remote contact with SEN advisors.&#10;4. Risk Assessments: If parents are unsure whether their children have been risk-assessed for attending support hubs, they should inquire with the school or local authority to ensure that appropriate risk assessments have been conducted and necessary measures are taken to support their children's health and well-being.&#10;5. Lockdown Rules and SEN Children: While there has been no specific mention of relaxing lockdown rules for children with special educational needs, the Welsh Government is open to considering measures to support these children in future phases of education in the new normal." />
    <node id=" is a professional expectation on all those that are working with our children and young people that, despite the circumstances they find themselves in, they should continue to report and refer cases if they see anything or hear or are told anything that makes them concerned about a child's welfare and safety. With regard to children with additional learning needs, I am aware that that can present a number of challenges to families and children, and perhaps Steve Davies could give some further details. We have been keen to work with local authorities to ensure specialist provision, where that is appropriate—so, if I could give you an example of my own local authority in Powys, they have two specialist centres available for children with more profound additional learning needs, and those centres are available—recognising, however, that, even with the provision of specialist hubs, it can be a challenge for some children with additional learning needs to find themselves outside of a routine. Hubs are often staffed on a rota basis and therefore children could be faced with staff that they are unfamiliar with. So, even when local authorities—and the vast, vast majority of them do—have specialist services in place, sometimes that might not be the best thing for a child's health and well-being. But perhaps Steve can give us further" />
    <edge source="1. Phased return: The Welsh government officials mentioned that the return to school will be phased, with priority given to the most vulnerable children, such as those with additional learning needs.&#10;&#10;2. Communication and confidence: A key challenge is ensuring clear communication with parents, staff, and students to build confidence in returning to school. This will involve providing evidence and information on which decisions are based, so that parents and staff feel assured of their safety.&#10;&#10;3. Safety measures: Decisions about reopening schools will be made considering the safety and well-being of children, young people, and staff. Measures may include social distancing, enhanced cleaning procedures, and altered school layouts to minimize contact between individuals.&#10;&#10;4. Testing and tracing: Widespread testing, tracing, and quarantine capabilities will be crucial in the next phase of managing the pandemic, as they are essential for ensuring safety in all aspects of society, including schools.&#10;&#10;5. Workforce availability: Ensuring adequate numbers of staff is a significant challenge, as some may be unable to return due to health concerns or other commitments. Strategies for addressing this issue will need to be developed and implemented.&#10;&#10;6. Social distancing in school settings: Implementing social distancing measures in schools will be challenging, given the young age and close proximity of many students. Creative solutions, such as staggered schedules, may be necessary to address this issue.&#10;&#10;7. School transportation: Ensuring safe transportation for students will require careful planning and management, including reduced capacity on buses and other forms of transport to maintain social distancing.&#10;&#10;8. Gathering at school gates: Preventing gatherings at school gates will be important for minimizing the risk of infection. Strategies may include designated drop-off and pick-up areas, as well 