    <edge source="1. Flexible Counseling Methods: The additional financial resources can be used to provide flexible counseling methods such as remote counseling via telephone and video support. This allows children and families to access counseling services while adhering to lockdown and social distancing rules.&#10;&#10;2. Remote Therapy Approaches: As restrictions are gradually removed, these funds can also be utilized to offer enhanced family therapy or therapy approaches in a manner that ensures safety and follows social distancing guidelines. The money does not necessarily have to be used for one-to-one counseling sessions and can be used to provide the best method of support for individual children and their families.&#10;&#10;3. Funding for Professional Development: A part of this additional funding will be allocated towards the professional learning and development of counsellors. This is crucial as counsellors may need to adapt their skills and abilities to work effectively within the confines of lockdown and social distancing rules, ensuring they can continue to provide much-needed support for children and young people dealing with fears and anxieties during this time.&#10;&#10;4. Increasing and Ramping up Services: The additional financial resources will help local authorities increase and ramp up services to support children and families in the immediacy of the lockdown situation, while also planning for a potential growth in demand for these services in the future. This proactive approach aims to put systems in place now rather than waiting for everything to return to normal." target=": Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Minister. It's encouraging to hear you talk about the ongoing safeguarding of children that are at home and I assume, within that, appropriate referral mechanisms are still in place if teachers or anybody has any particular concern about a child. Similarly, with special educational needs, whereas some of those children benefit clea