    <edge source=" additional financial resources, and we've been very pleased to be able to secure that for them.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: So, that would include things like telephone and video support as well, I guess, then.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, absolutely. So, that would include remote counselling as in a fashion that we're doing now, but also, as and when some of the restrictions are perhaps removed, looking at an enhanced family therapy, or a therapy approach. So, when we talk about counselling, I think it's important to recognise that there will be some flexibility around this money and it does not necessarily mean that local authorities have to use it on a one-to-one basis. That might not be appropriate for some children, especially our younger children and their families, and they can use that money to provide counselling or therapy—in the widest possible terms—that is the best method to support individual children and their families. But, clearly, we're having to do that in the confines of lockdown and social distancing at the moment. Some of that money can also be used to support the professional learning and the professional development of counsellors, because, of course, they may be being asked" target="1. Maintain contact and discuss support: Even if the school or local authority has not reached out, parents should proactively contact them to discuss available support for their children with additional learning needs. This may include one-on-one provisions, remote working strategies, or referral mechanisms if there are concerns about the child's well-being.&#10;2. Flexible counselling and therapy: Local authorities can use allocated financial resources flexibly to provide various forms of counselling and therapy that best suit individual children and families, including remote counseling and, when possible, enhanced family therapy.&#10;3. Support for health needs: For children with intense health needs who must stay at home, local authorities and education systems are looking for ways to support them and their families in various ways, including regular check-ins and telephone contact.&#10;4. Guidelines for parents: The 'Stay Safe. Stay Learning' policy statement provides advice to parents and carers on the Hwb platform regarding supporting their children's learning at home. However, specific guidelines on recommended hours of home learning or volume of work per day have not been explicitly mentioned in the transcript.&#10;5. Increased demand for services: Additional financial resources are being made available to local authorities to increase and ramp up services to support children and families during this time, including potential growth in the number of children requiring support due to fears and anxieties related to the pandemic situation. There is a recognition that some traditional methods of delivering services may not be possible due to social distancing rules, but efforts are being made to put systems in place now and plan for future increased demand.">
