    <edge source="1. Dawn Bowden AM is temporarily chairing the meeting.&#10;2. The agenda for the evidence session this afternoon includes:&#10;   - A welcome and opening statement from Kirsty Williams AM, Minister for Education.&#10;   - An appreciation statement from the Minister regarding those who have helped during the pandemic, particularly those who have kept school hubs open, looked after vulnerable children, and the children of key workers.&#10;   - A discussion with Kirsty Williams AM, Steve Davies (director of the education directorate), and Huw Morris (group director, skills, higher education and lifelong learning) on the impact of the coronavirus epidemic on education in Wales." target="1. The Welsh Government is aware of its responsibilities towards children's rights and is taking steps to ensure equal opportunity and access to learning during this time.&#10;2. Previous investments have provided a strong base, such as the Hwb digital learning platform and national purchasing of Microsoft Office and Google for Education tools.&#10;3. Adobe Spark has been deployed nationally, but access to hardware and connectivity is crucial. Officials are working with local authorities to ensure all children have access to necessary hardware and connectivity.&#10;4. The Welsh Government is concerned about the potential increase in the attainment gap between disadvantaged pupils and their more affluent peers due to unequal access to technology. Measures will be considered when developing future phases of education in the new normal.">
