    <edge source=" the Universities UK document that explains some of the difficulties that they're going to be running into if this proceeds much further. My understanding is that the main emphasis at the moment is to try and get all the universities across the UK through this initial period of difficulty by releasing as much money as possible. I can see that your figure to the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales was a little bit down on last year's letter—not that there's been a remit letter yet, but an indication. Are you releasing that money earlier so that they can use it more swiftly, or does that not matter?&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Before you come in, Minister, that is going to have to be the last question, just to make you aware of that, because we are coming up to the end of our time.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. That's fine.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Of course, Suzy, we are working closely with Universities Wales and have a lot of sympathy for the proposals that have come forward from Universities UK, which Wales's universities have been a part of forming. Stability in the first instance is really important to us, which is why we've been" target="1. Discussions are taking place between the Welsh Government, NUS Wales, and counterparts across the UK regarding financial support for students impacted by changes in their study arrangements due to the pandemic.&#10;2. There will be no change to student support payments for students who have left their universities and decided to go home.&#10;3. The Welsh Government continues to pay Education Maintenance Allowance (EMA) at this time for FE students who are eligible, even though there is an attendance requirement which is not appropriate to enforce at the moment.&#10;4. Officials are in touch with UCAS, and the Welsh Minister for Education has had meetings with representatives of the Welsh higher education sector to discuss these matters.&#10;5. The Welsh Government advises students to have discussions with their accommodation providers about waiving or partially waiving accommodation fees where appropriate.&#10;6. The Welsh Government is working with representatives of the HE sector to include them in these approaches and keep them apprised of the situation, as they may wish to implement similar measures within their own institutions.">
