    <edge source=" the Universities UK document that explains some of the difficulties that they're going to be running into if this proceeds much further. My understanding is that the main emphasis at the moment is to try and get all the universities across the UK through this initial period of difficulty by releasing as much money as possible. I can see that your figure to the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales was a little bit down on last year's letter—not that there's been a remit letter yet, but an indication. Are you releasing that money earlier so that they can use it more swiftly, or does that not matter?&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Before you come in, Minister, that is going to have to be the last question, just to make you aware of that, because we are coming up to the end of our time.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. That's fine.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Of course, Suzy, we are working closely with Universities Wales and have a lot of sympathy for the proposals that have come forward from Universities UK, which Wales's universities have been a part of forming. Stability in the first instance is really important to us, which is why we've been" target="1. The Welsh Government, along with Universities Wales and representatives of the Welsh higher education sector, are aiming to provide stability for the next academic year and support the sector through these challenging times. This includes releasing as much money as possible to help universities get through this initial period of difficulty.&#10;2. Discussions are taking place between relevant bodies in Wales, Northern Ireland, Scotland, and the Westminster Government, as well as UCAS, to address issues related to student entry into universities due to the pandemic.&#10;3. Officials are working with UCAS, and the Welsh Minister for Education has met with representatives of the Welsh higher education sector to discuss these matters. The Welsh Government advises students to have discussions with their accommodation providers about waiving or partially waiving accommodation fees where appropriate.&#10;4. There is ongoing collaboration between the Welsh Government, NUS Wales, and counterparts across the UK to provide financial support for students impacted by changes in their study arrangements due to the pandemic.&#10;5. The Welsh Government continues to pay Education Maintenance Allowance (EMA) at this time for FE students who are eligible, even though there is an attendance requirement which is not appropriate to enforce at the moment.&#10;6. A four-nation approach will be crucial in addressing the impact on the HE sector, as significant figures have been discussed regarding the potential impact of the pandemic on higher education.">
