    <edge source=" the Universities UK document that explains some of the difficulties that they're going to be running into if this proceeds much further. My understanding is that the main emphasis at the moment is to try and get all the universities across the UK through this initial period of difficulty by releasing as much money as possible. I can see that your figure to the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales was a little bit down on last year's letter—not that there's been a remit letter yet, but an indication. Are you releasing that money earlier so that they can use it more swiftly, or does that not matter?&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Before you come in, Minister, that is going to have to be the last question, just to make you aware of that, because we are coming up to the end of our time.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. That's fine.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Of course, Suzy, we are working closely with Universities Wales and have a lot of sympathy for the proposals that have come forward from Universities UK, which Wales's universities have been a part of forming. Stability in the first instance is really important to us, which is why we've been" target="1. The Welsh Government, in collaboration with Universities Wales and representatives of the Welsh higher education sector, is aiming to provide stability for the next academic year and support the sector through these challenging times by releasing as much money as possible to help universities get through this initial period of difficulty. This aligns with one of the key proposals from Universities UK, which emphasizes the need for financial support to ensure university sustainability.&#10;2. The Welsh Government is also participating in discussions with relevant bodies in Wales, Northern Ireland, Scotland, and the Westminster Government, as well as UCAS, to address issues related to student entry into universities due to the pandemic. This includes discussions on the moratorium on unconditional offers for university admission, which is another concern raised by Universities UK.&#10;3. Additionally, the Welsh Government is working with NUS Wales and counterparts across the UK to provide financial support for students impacted by changes in their study arrangements due to the pandemic. This addresses another issue raised by Universities UK, which highlights the need for student financial support during this time. The Welsh Government's efforts demonstrate a commitment to addressing the challenges faced by both universities and students in light of the pandemic, with measures that are consistent with the proposals put forward by Universities UK.">
