    <edge source=": Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Since yesterday, the Welsh Government has started publishing data on the number of schools that are open, the number of children attending those schools, and the number of staff involved, and they have been making this information available as per capita of the population. On average, I think it's 1 per cent of the children of Wales that actually attend these locations, and some 5 per cent of the staff. So, can you analyse those figures a little further? Can you tell us how many children, according to this data, are children of key workers, and how many are vulnerable children?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Thank you very much, Siân. As you quite rightly say, on average, we have 518 school hubs open each day, with up to 4,200 children attending. We have seen an increase in the number of attendances since the start of what would have been the traditional summer term. We have approximately 5.6 per cent of the teaching population working in those hubs, and at present, 85 per cent of the children who are attending are the children of key workers, the remainder being vulnerable children. So, we are now averaging 600 vulnerable children per day. These are" target="Based on the meeting transcript, it appears that there has been an increase in the number of vulnerable children attending schools during the crisis and lockdown. After the Easter break, the number of vulnerable children doubled, but this does not necessarily mean that all of these children were new to the schools or hubs. Some of them may have been previously enrolled but did not attend over the break.&#10;&#10;The Welsh Government has been publishing data on the number of schools open and the number of children attending, with an average of 1% of children in Wales attending these locations and 5% of the staff. Of the children attending, 85% are children of key workers, while the remaining 15% are vulnerable children. This translates to approximately 600 vulnerable children per day.&#10;&#10;It is also mentioned that there has been an evolution in the approach to supporting vulnerable children since the start of the crisis, with local authorities and schools working quickly to set up hubs. The situation continues to evolve, and the Welsh Government expects schools to remain in contact with children, identify vulnerable children, and refer them to children's services if needed.">
