    <edge source="Based on the meeting transcript, it appears that there has been an increase in the number of vulnerable children attending schools during the crisis and lockdown. After the Easter break, the number of vulnerable children doubled, but this does not necessarily mean that all of these children were new to the schools or hubs. Some of them may have been previously enrolled but did not attend over the break.&#10;&#10;The Welsh Government has been publishing data on the number of schools open and the number of children attending, with an average of 1% of children in Wales attending these locations and 5% of the staff. Of the children attending, 85% are children of key workers, while the remaining 15% are vulnerable children. This translates to approximately 600 vulnerable children per day.&#10;&#10;It is also mentioned that there has been an evolution in the approach to supporting vulnerable children since the start of the crisis, with local authorities and schools working quickly to set up hubs. The situation continues to evolve, and the Welsh Government expects schools to remain in contact with children, identify vulnerable children, and refer them to children's services if needed." target="1. Flexible counseling methods: The Welsh Government plans to provide flexible counseling methods such as remote counseling via telephone and video support. This will allow children and families to access counseling services while adhering to lockdown and social distancing rules.&#10;2. Remote therapy approaches: As restrictions are gradually removed, funds will be utilized to offer enhanced family therapy or therapy approaches in a manner that ensures safety and follows social distancing guidelines. The money does not necessarily have to be used for one-to-one counseling sessions and can be used to provide the best method of support for individual children and their families.&#10;3. Funding for professional development: A part of this additional funding will be allocated towards the professional learning and development of counsellors. This is crucial as counsellors may need to adapt their skills and abilities to work effectively within the confines of lockdown and social distancing rules, ensuring they can continue to provide much-needed support for children and young people dealing with fears and anxieties during this time.&#10;4. Increasing and ramping up services: The additional financial resources will help local authorities increase and ramp up services to support children and families in the immediacy of the lockdown situation, while also planning for a potential growth in demand for these services in the future. This proactive approach aims to put systems in place now rather than waiting for everything to return to normal.">
