    <edge source="1. Discussions are taking place between the Welsh Government, NUS Wales, and counterparts across the UK regarding financial support for students impacted by changes in their study arrangements due to the pandemic.&#10;2. There will be no change to student support payments for students who have left their universities and decided to go home.&#10;3. The Welsh Government continues to pay Education Maintenance Allowance (EMA) at this time for FE students who are eligible, even though there is an attendance requirement which is not appropriate to enforce at the moment.&#10;4. Officials are in touch with UCAS, and the Welsh Minister for Education has had meetings with representatives of the Welsh higher education sector to discuss these matters.&#10;5. The Welsh Government advises students to have discussions with their accommodation providers about waiving or partially waiving accommodation fees where appropriate.&#10;6. The Welsh Government is working with representatives of the HE sector to include them in these approaches and keep them apprised of the situation, as they may wish to implement similar measures within their own institutions." target=" on weekends or working in the evenings, or whatever, so their income has been impacted. Just in the round, what kind of conversations are happening around that? Again, it's probably a four-nation approach, I would imagine.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Suzy. You are correct to say that our student support regime does allow for a lower payment to be made to those students that stay at home during their studies, but I want to reassure students that there will be no change to their student support payments just because they have left their universities and have decided to go home. There should be no change. Also, we are continuing, it should be important to say, to pay education maintenance allowance at this time for our FE students that are eligible for that, even though, obviously,