    <edge source="Based on the meeting transcript, the Welsh Government is aware that some children with special educational needs (SEN) may not respond as well to remote learning. However, no specific mention has been made about a relaxation of lockdown rules for these children. Instead, the focus is on ensuring appropriate referral mechanisms are in place for teachers or anyone who has concerns about a child, and that schools should continue to identify vulnerable children and refer them to children's services if needed. There is also an expectation for schools to remain in contact with children during this time. While there has been no explicit mention of relaxing lockdown rules for children with SEN, the Welsh Government seems open to considering measures to support these children in future phases of education in the new normal." target="1. Professional Expectations for Reporting and Referring Cases: There is a professional expectation for all those working with children and young people, including in specialist hubs, to continue reporting and referring cases if they have concerns about a child's welfare and safety. This responsibility applies even during the current circumstances when face-to-face contact may be limited.&#10;2. Challenges in Specialist Hubs: Specialist hubs for children with additional learning needs can present challenges related to staffing. These hubs often operate on a rota basis, which means that children might interact with staff they are unfamiliar with, potentially impacting their health and well-being.&#10;3. Importance of Maintaining Communication: To support children with additional learning needs during this time, it is essential for schools to maintain regular contact with them. This can help keep children engaged and supported, especially for young children who might not respond well to remote contact with SEN advisors.&#10;4. Risk Assessments: If parents are unsure whether their children have been risk-assessed for attending support hubs, they should inquire with the school or local authority to ensure that appropriate risk assessments have been conducted and necessary measures are taken to support their children's health and well-being.&#10;5. Lockdown Rules and SEN Children: While there has been no specific mention of relaxing lockdown rules for children with special educational needs, the Welsh Government is open to considering measures to support these children in future phases of education in the new normal.">
