    <edge source="1. Professional Expectations for Reporting and Referring Cases: There is a professional expectation for all those working with children and young people, including in specialist hubs, to continue reporting and referring cases if they have concerns about a child's welfare and safety. This responsibility applies even during the current circumstances when face-to-face contact may be limited.&#10;2. Challenges in Specialist Hubs: Specialist hubs for children with additional learning needs can present challenges related to staffing. These hubs often operate on a rota basis, which means that children might interact with staff they are unfamiliar with, potentially impacting their health and well-being.&#10;3. Importance of Maintaining Communication: To support children with additional learning needs during this time, it is essential for schools to maintain regular contact with them. This can help keep children engaged and supported, especially for young children who might not respond well to remote contact with SEN advisors.&#10;4. Risk Assessments: If parents are unsure whether their children have been risk-assessed for attending support hubs, they should inquire with the school or local authority to ensure that appropriate risk assessments have been conducted and necessary measures are taken to support their children's health and well-being.&#10;5. Lockdown Rules and SEN Children: While there has been no specific mention of relaxing lockdown rules for children with special educational needs, the Welsh Government is open to considering measures to support these children in future phases of education in the new normal." target=" is a professional expectation on all those that are working with our children and young people that, despite the circumstances they find themselves in, they should continue to report and refer cases if they see anything or hear or are told anything that makes them concerned about a child's welfare and safety. With regard to children with additional learning needs, I am aware that that can present a number of challenges to families and children, and perhaps Steve Davies could give some further details. We have been keen to work with local authorities to ensure specialist provision, where that is appropriate—so, if I could give you an example of my own local authority in Powys, they have two specialist centres available for children with more profound additional learning needs, and those centres are available—recognising, however, that, even with the provision of specialist hubs, it can be a challenge for some children with additional learning needs to find themselves outside of a routine. Hubs are often staffed on a rota basis and therefore children could be faced with staff that they are unfamiliar with. So, even when local authorities—and the vast, vast majority of them do—have specialist services in place, sometimes that might not be the best thing for a child's health and well-being. But perhaps Steve can give us further">
